  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Defining Client Components**\n\nOkay, I\'m now focused on the client-side component architecture. I am committed to clean views with a modular design. To start, I\'m listing the views/pages. The first is a catalog, which will display a product grid with filtering, sorting and quick toggle actions.\n\n\n**Outlining Client-Side Views**\n\nI\'ve outlined crucial client-side views. Product details showcase imagery, descriptions, and user reviews. The cart features quantity adjustments and promo code application. Checkout includes shipping details, order breakdown, and a mock-card payment interface. \"My Orders\" tracks order history with payment and shipping statuses. An admin panel will provide stats and catalog management tools for adding, editing, and deleting products with image uploading.\n\n\n**Adding Order Management**\n\nNow, I\'m integrating an order management view. I envision a table that lists all system orders, and implements controls for cycling through shipping statuses, from \"pending\" to \"shipped\" to \"delivered.\" My focus is on clear, concise status transitions. The goal here is efficient order handling.\n\nI\'m thinking about auth forms now! These will involve a login and registration page. They should automatically switch back to the original page or home on successful login, and provide clear error messages with toast alerts on failures.\n\nFinally, I\'m starting to organize those views to make them modular to avoid bloating files. I want clean and modular code files. So, I will start by separating into these components. I\'ll make: a `Navbar` to hold user state, logo, links, dynamic badge counts, admin portal quick links, and a logout action. There will be a `ProductCard` displaying product information. And finally, an `AdminStatsView` displaying summary data and charts.\n\n\n**Defining Component Features**\n\nI am now focusing on the detailed feature-set for several key components. I\'m developing `/src/components/AdminProductsView.tsx` with a product table and standard forms for adding/editing products. `/src/components/AdminOrdersView.tsx` will include a table for system orders with shipping state dropdowns. There will be a `ReviewSection.tsx` with detailed reviews and a form with star selections, and `CheckoutForm.tsx` with address forms and a mock credit card visualizer. I\'ve also starting mapping a simple `src/App.tsx` router.\n\n\n**Implementing Hash Router**\n\nMy recent focus has been on implementing a hash-based router. I\'ve built a robust system that\'s bug-free and handles history states without extra dependencies. I\'m leveraging `useEffect` to manage hash changes, ensuring synchronization with back-button navigation.\n\n\n**Adding Toast Notifications**\n\nI\'m now integrating a toast notification system into `App.tsx`\'s state for user feedback. I will have a toast list and a `showToast(msg, type)` helper. The goal is to provide beautiful, Tailwind-styled alerts with `motion` for visual flair, supporting common feedback use cases. I need to make sure the library versions are compatible.\n\n\n"
    modified_response: "I will create the global Header Navigation component `/src/components/Navbar.tsx` with dynamic badge counts, admin portal access indicators, user profile information, and elegant transition visual states using `motion/react`."
    thinking_duration {
      seconds: 9
      nanos: 250450384
    }
