  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Building App.tsx**\n\nI\'m making excellent headway on this. The underlying structure feels incredibly modular, robust, and clean. Now, I\'ve started tackling `/src/App.tsx`, focusing on its core responsibilities. I\'m focusing on handling crucial state parameters, including `user` of type `User | null` and `token` which is of type `string | null`.\n\n\n**Defining App State**\n\nNow I\'m diving deeper into the application\'s state. I\'ve defined `cart` as `CartItem[]`, and decided to persist it in `localStorage`. I\'m also including `products` as `Product[]`, `orders` as `Order[]`, and `adminStats` as `AdminStats | null`. I need to track the `currentView` as a `string`, with flexible `viewParams`. The wishlist will use an array of product IDs and I\'ve also incorporated coupons.\n\n\n**Implementing Core Views**\n\nI\'m now focusing on core views, starting with a high-fidelity checkout form and mock credit card payment integration. The user\'s order history is the next priority. I\'ve also outlined the admin portal\'s dashboard view, with its tabbed structure for stats, products, and orders. I am also working on the login and register forms, to handle user authentication.\n\\n\\n\nMy next thought is on creating a robust API client with standard fetch methods, I will implement `fetchProducts`, `fetchOrders`, `login`, and `register` first, along with core methods for user interaction like placing orders and toggling the wishlist. The product reviews component is also in progress.\n\n\n**Refining Product Interactions**\n\nI\'ve just implemented product reviews and ratings, making for a fully interactive review panel within product details. I\'ve also implemented a coupon and discount system, allowing customers to apply codes like \"SAVE10\" or \"WELCOME50\" in the cart screen. I\'ve also added pagination for products, building a simple pagination system on the client-side for smooth user experience. Finally, I\'ve implemented loading states in the UI, complete with spinning wheels, skeletons, and transaction animations, to enhance user experience. Now, I will begin modifying `/src/App.tsx` file for premium e-commerce logic, after reviewing it\'s contents, and using imports from `motion/react`, `lucide-react`, and our custom sub-components.\n\n\n"
    modified_response: "I will implement the main `/src/App.tsx` application component, writing the core state manager, hash routing engine, API client methods, toast notifications, and client-side view routers. This file binds together the landing catalog, item details, promo coupons, checkout flow, historic logs, and administration panel into a single-page full-stack React experience."
    thinking_duration {
      seconds: 6
      nanos: 338127802
    }
