ng to the compiler misinterpreting `ProductCard`. I\'m also looking at the impact of the import on the root component.\n\n\n**Testing the Casting**\n\nI\'ve tested casting `ProductCard` to `any` within `App.tsx` and it compiled perfectly, resolving the typing conflict seamlessly. It\'s a remarkably clean solution to sidestepping React 19\'s stricter JSX type enforcement, especially with `framer-motion` integrations. Now I am checking whether casting sub-components also will lead to bulletproof compilation. I\'m reviewing lines 736 to 748 in `App.tsx` again.\n\n\n**Confirming a Solution**\n\nI\'m now zeroing in on a cleaner approach. Instead of broad casting to `any`, I\'m looking at selective type assertion within the component that caused the `key` prop error. This is to get the best of both worlds, avoiding excessive casting and allowing for bulletproof compilation in React 19 / TS 5. I think the issue is the return type of `motion.div` from `motion/react`. It will resolve the strict JSX type enforcement.\n\n\n"
